WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.870
CHRISTINE BREINER: Welcome
back to recitation.

00:00:08.870 --> 00:00:12.850
In this video, I'd like us to
practice integration by parts.

00:00:12.850 --> 00:00:15.580
Specifically, I'd like to
solve the following four

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:18.490
problems. Or I'd like you to
solve the following four

00:00:18.490 --> 00:00:22.090
problems. I'd like us to find
antiderivatives for each of

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:26.340
these functions. x e to the
minus x, x cubed over the

00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:31.160
quantity 1 plus x squared
squared, arc tan x, and

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:33.540
natural log x over x squared.

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:36.420
And so the main goal, because
we're using integration by

00:00:36.420 --> 00:00:39.090
parts, is to figure out what
you should make u, and what

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:40.970
you should make v prime.

00:00:40.970 --> 00:00:42.810
And why don't you
give it a shot.

00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:43.860
Work on that for a little bit.

00:00:43.860 --> 00:00:46.550
I'm actually going to give you
one hint, and that's that this

00:00:46.550 --> 00:00:49.140
one, you may want to break up
in a nontraditional way.

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:51.750
You may not want to break
it up as x cubed

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:53.350
and 1 over this function.

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:55.140
You're going to want
to split up this

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:56.930
function in the numerator.

00:00:56.930 --> 00:01:00.200
Part of it will be in u, part
of it will be in v prime.

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:02.300
So that's my hint on number 2.

00:01:02.300 --> 00:01:04.180
So now with that information,
I'd like you to give it a

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:06.890
shot, and then I'll come back,
and I'll show you how I do it.

00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:16.050
OK, welcome back.

00:01:16.050 --> 00:01:18.360
So again, what we're looking
for is antiderivatives for

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:21.180
each of these four functions.

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:23.590
And now, what I'm going to do,
is I'm going to help you pick

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:26.400
u and v prime, and then
I'm going to show you

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:27.680
what answer I got.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:30.140
And I'm going to let you do
the work in the middle.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:32.890
So let's start off
with number 1.

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:40.120
So if I have xe to the minus x
integral of xe to the minus x

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:45.280
dx, it's very easy to do either,
to make either e to

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:47.100
the minus x either
u or v prime.

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:48.330
Doesn't really matter.

00:01:48.330 --> 00:01:51.630
Because an integral of e to the
minus x is going to have

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:54.000
an e to the minus x again, and
a derivative is going to have

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.280
an e to the minus x again, with
a minus sign in front, in

00:01:57.280 --> 00:01:58.010
both cases.

00:01:58.010 --> 00:01:59.740
But this doesn't
really change.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.440
So we have, when we go up or
down, it doesn't really matter

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:04.430
if we integrate up or
take a derivative.

00:02:04.430 --> 00:02:07.200
So really it's, we get to pick
what we do with the c to the

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:09.610
minus x based on what we
want to do with the x.

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:12.450
Well, we like taking derivatives
of things that

00:02:12.450 --> 00:02:16.710
don't have two functions of x,
so it would be nice if we

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:20.600
chose our integration by parts
pieces so that this thing

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:22.280
wasn't there anymore.

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:24.280
So let me write down, actually,
before I even do

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:26.360
number 1, maybe I should
remind you what the

00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:28.590
integration by parts
formula is.

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:31.010
So let me just, I'll scratch
that out for a second.

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:32.810
And what we're doing, is we're
going to have integral

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:35.870
of u v prime dx.

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:38.220
And if you recall what you saw
in lecture, is this should be

00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:44.240
equal to uv minus the integral
v u prime dx.

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:47.000
And we'll put that plus c,
because sometimes I forget to

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:47.740
write it at the end.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:49.890
So I'll put it there,
so I don't forget.

00:02:49.890 --> 00:02:52.045
So really, what we're trying
to do, right, is pick the u

00:02:52.045 --> 00:02:53.540
and v prime.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:56.300
And so we want to make this
thing, this v u prime, as

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:58.030
simple as possible.

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:00.700
So what I was saying is if we
make this v prime or this u,

00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:01.870
it doesn't matter.

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:05.820
So let's pick whether we want
this to be u or v prime.

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:09.930
Well, if I make this u,
then u prime is 1.

00:03:09.930 --> 00:03:10.900
That's good.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:14.450
If I make it v prime, then
v is x squared over 2.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:15.690
That's more complicated.

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:18.480
So we obviously want
to make this u.

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:23.370
So for number 1, we're going to
choose u is equal to x, and

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:28.520
v prime is equal to
e to the minus x.

00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:30.650
And then you can proceed
from there.

00:03:30.650 --> 00:03:32.270
And I'll leave it at that.

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:34.890
Well, actually, just to make
sure we're OK, I'll even write

00:03:34.890 --> 00:03:38.350
u prime is equal to 1, and
v is going to be equal to

00:03:38.350 --> 00:03:40.750
negative e to the minus x.

00:03:40.750 --> 00:03:43.120
So we'd be able to proceed
from there, right?

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:46.020
We have all the pieces
we need.

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:47.010
Now, number 2--

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:50.420
I'll give you the final
answers at the end.

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:52.540
Number 2, picking u and v
prime is a little more

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:53.760
complicated.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:56.920
And let's look at
this function.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.138
x cubed over 1 plus
x squared squared.

00:04:00.138 --> 00:04:01.388
The problem with picking--

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:04.090
that does not look like a 2.

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:04.660
Sorry.

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:07.980
The problem with picking u and
v prime here, is that it's

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:10.780
hard to see what's going to
be easy to integrate.

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:15.070
So what we want to do
is rewrite this as--

00:04:15.070 --> 00:04:24.840
let's see-- x squared times x
over 1 plus x squared squared.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:27.380
And now, why is this
any better?

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:28.740
Well, I mean, it's
the same thing.

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:31.370
But why does this help us
see what we want to do?

00:04:31.370 --> 00:04:34.710
Well, if you notice this
thing right here--

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:35.770
1 plus x squared.

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.020
What is its derivative?

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:39.260
Its derivative is 2x.

00:04:39.260 --> 00:04:40.960
Up here we have an x.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:45.150
So this piece right here looks
like it could be much more

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:49.120
easily integrated then
this right here.

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:52.180
So this might be a little
counterintuitive, because

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:54.400
we're going to take the
harder-looking thing, and make

00:04:54.400 --> 00:04:56.990
that our v prime.

00:04:56.990 --> 00:04:59.620
But the nice thing is
that we can actually

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:01.340
integrate this quantity.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:07.400
So we choose, in this case,
this is our u, and

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:10.340
this is our v prime.

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:11.270
So how do I integrate this?

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.660
Well, I integrate this by
using a substitution.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:16.360
And that will give me v. And
the derivative of this is

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:16.970
quite simple.

00:05:16.970 --> 00:05:17.410
It's just 2x.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:18.610
Right?

00:05:18.610 --> 00:05:20.550
But this is the strategy
that we want here.

00:05:20.550 --> 00:05:23.400
Why did we even think to split
that up like that?

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:26.080
Well, we knew we had to deal
with the denominator in some

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:29.410
fashion, and taking a derivative
with this in the

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:34.040
denominator, so putting this
part of the function in u--

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:36.370
when I look at u prime, it's
going to be even worse.

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:38.470
It's going to be a higher
power here.

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:40.720
It's going to be a cubic
in the denominator.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:42.160
That's just making
things worse.

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:44.830
So we know we'd like to
integrate this denominator.

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:46.870
We'd like it to be a
part of v prime.

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:50.850
But the problem is that if I put
all the x cubed in the u,

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:54.440
and if I just had a 1 here for
my v prime, that's, I can't

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:55.820
really integrate
that very well.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:58.790
But if I keep one of the x's,
then I can integrate this

00:05:58.790 --> 00:06:00.920
quite simply with
a substitution.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:03.640
So that's the sort of reasoning
behind why we choose

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:04.990
it that way.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:05.350
All right.

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:07.170
We've got two more to look
at, and then I'll

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:09.720
give you the answers.

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:10.530
3.

00:06:10.530 --> 00:06:10.850
OK.

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:13.410
3, you've seen this
trick before.

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:16.500
The function was arc tan x.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:19.800
Now, you've seen this trick
I'm about to do with

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:21.280
natural log of x.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:23.170
The same kind of thing with
natural log of x.

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:26.250
You actually saw this in one
of the lecture videos.

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:27.900
Because there's only one
function here, you might

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:31.110
think, well, I have no idea what
I'm supposed to pick for

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:32.330
u and v prime.

00:06:32.330 --> 00:06:36.490
But remember, it's really
arc tan x times 1.

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:39.120
Now I have two functions.

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:43.260
And what gives us a hint for why
we would want to do this,

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.840
is that what's the derivative
of arc tan x?

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:47.197
Let me just remind you.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:56.410
d dx of arc tan x is 1 over
1 plus x squared.

00:06:56.410 --> 00:06:57.970
Right?

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:00.490
We're back to actually an almost
similar situation to

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:02.560
what we had in the
previous thing.

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:04.990
d dx of arc tan x is 1 over
1 plus x squared.

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:08.640
So taking a derivative of this
puts it in a form that almost

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:09.600
looks easy to integrate.

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:11.920
What would make this function
easy to integrate?

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:14.310
If there was an x up here,
instead of a 1.

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:15.830
Then I could use substitution.

00:07:15.830 --> 00:07:18.710
Where do we get that x from
when we're solving this

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:20.940
problem, where we're
actually finding an

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.930
antiderivative of arc tan x?

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:27.070
Well, it's going to come from
the fact that I make this u,

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:29.210
and I make 1 v prime.

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:31.620
So let me write that
out explicitly.

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:36.790
u I make arc tan x, and
v prime I make 1.

00:07:36.790 --> 00:07:38.910
What does that do
in our formula?

00:07:38.910 --> 00:07:41.550
Well, we're going to
be integrating

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:44.990
something that is v u prime.

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:49.070
Well, v is going to be x, and
u prime we see right here.

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:51.530
So it's going to be, I'm going
to be integrating x over 1

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:53.470
plus x squared when I
started doing the

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:55.200
integration by parts method.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:57.500
That's much simpler, as we
talked about previously,

00:07:57.500 --> 00:07:59.830
because the derivative of x
squared is 2x, and you have an

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:03.250
x in the numerator when
you put in that v.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:07.190
So this is sort of the flavor
of how these things are

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:08.475
actually working.

00:08:08.475 --> 00:08:12.410
So let me do the
final one here.

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:16.950
We have ln x over x squared.

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:17.960
OK.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:20.240
Let me just tell
you right now.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:23.290
In integration by parts, natural
log x is not something

00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:25.360
you want to make the v prime.

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:27.180
You don't want to try and
take an antiderivative.

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:30.480
You know an antiderivative
of natural log of x.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:31.560
x ln x minus x.

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:34.660
But that's certainly not going
to make things any easier.

00:08:34.660 --> 00:08:34.720
Right?

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:37.900
You're actually, then you've got
a product of two functions

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:38.460
all of a sudden.

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:40.700
Everything's getting
more complicated.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:43.490
But natural log of x has a very
nice derivative, because

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:46.300
you end up with something that
has just a power of x.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:49.540
Derivative of natural log
of x, just 1 over x.

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:52.720
So that's probably the way you
always want to go when you see

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:55.370
natural log of x in these
integration by parts

00:08:55.370 --> 00:08:56.650
techniques.

00:08:56.650 --> 00:09:01.730
Because if I choose u is equal
to ln x, and then v prime.

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:04.890
In this case, I'm going to
write it as a power.

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:06.690
Let's think about
what happened.

00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:09.050
u prime is 1 over x, right?

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:11.500
So u prime is x to
the minus 1.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:12.430
What's v?

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:14.900
Well, it's something
like, let's see.

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:16.340
Negative x to the minus 1.

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:17.340
Something like that, right?

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:18.710
Let's make sure I
did that right.

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:20.410
Yeah, I think I did
that right.

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:23.770
So all of a sudden, if I
integrate v u prime, that's

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:24.750
just a power rule.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:27.820
It's x to the minus 2, negative
x to the minus 2.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:31.120
So that's quite easy
to integrate.

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:35.150
So again, when I see natural log
of x in an integration by

00:09:35.150 --> 00:09:39.400
parts method, almost always, I
hate to say always, almost

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.210
always, almost a guarantee
that you want to take a

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:42.050
derivative.

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:45.030
You want to make that the u.

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:47.300
So hopefully that makes sense,
some of these strategies.

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:50.110
I tried to pick ones that were
somewhat different, so you

00:09:50.110 --> 00:09:52.950
could see some different types
of strategies we needed.

00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:54.830
And now I've done
these earlier.

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:56.760
So I'm just going to write down
what the answers actually

00:09:56.760 --> 00:10:01.050
are, and you can compare
to what you got.

00:10:01.050 --> 00:10:03.064
So the answer to number
1, just to check.

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:11.430
Number 2.

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:13.200
Some of these are
kind of long.

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:28.160
Number 3.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:38.160
Number 4.

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:46.736
So let's just go through.

00:10:46.736 --> 00:10:50.370
We get, In number 1, we get
negative x e to the minus x

00:10:50.370 --> 00:10:52.930
minus e to the minus x plus c.

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:56.300
Number 2, we get negative x
squared over 2 times 1 plus x

00:10:56.300 --> 00:11:01.480
squared plus 1/2 natural log
1 plus x squared plus c.

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:06.210
3 is x arc tan x minus 1/2
natural log of the quantity 1

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:10.400
plus x squared plus c, and 4 is
negative natural log x over

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:15.290
x minus 1 over x plus c.

00:11:15.290 --> 00:11:18.640
So again, the whole point of
this exercise, in my mind, is

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:21.800
really to make sure we get a
good understanding of, when

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:24.440
we're doing integration by
parts, which function makes

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:27.115
the most sense to have as u, and
which function makes the

00:11:27.115 --> 00:11:28.280
most sense to have as v prime.

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:30.470
So that was the main point
of this exercise.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.770
Hopefully you're starting to
get a flavor for how these

00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:35.340
problems actually work.

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:37.770
And I think I will stop there.